The WebSearch tool returns up-to-date information from the web. It exposes two capabilities, picked per call via `command`. Each call performs **one** operation.

## Definitions

- **`search`** — runs the configured search engine and returns SERP rows (URL, domain, title, snippet). Use to discover candidate URLs for a `gap`.
- **`read_urls`** — crawls 1–3 URLs and returns full-page text. Use to capitalize when a SERP returned promising URLs but snippets don't close the gap; also when the user pasted a URL or exact figures / quotes / specs are required.

## Key guidelines

- **Chaining vs parallel.** Chain calls for sequential gaps; issue parallel calls in the same turn for independent gaps (one `search` per distinct `gap`).
- **Query craft.** `query` is a **short keyword line** (~3–8 words, ≤80 chars) — not the user's question and not the `gap` text. Put reasoning in `gap` / `objective`. Drop fillers; use `"quotes"` and operators (`site:`, `-term`, `filetype:pdf`) when useful.
- **Query language.** Start in the user's question language; switch language only as a refinement when the first SERP for a locale-specific gap returned no on-topic results (use native names verbatim when you do).
- **Batching.** Put 2–3 complementary URLs in one `read_urls` call. Re-searching the *same* gap with rephrased keywords when the previous SERP already had a credible URL is wasteful — fetch instead.

## Anti-pattern

Re-searching the same gap with synonyms when a credible URL is already on the SERP — fetch it.

